USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost comical how Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, is repeating the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, whom he himself considered the dumbest.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it over the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years earlier.
Not only does he use the phrase "just like Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the Bush declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Way Forward", without hesitation.
The Commission has also been working on the drafting of a new European strategy for the fight against drugs, which will be presented to the European Parliament in the spring.
The following months, however, showed that the Bush strategy, based on recommendations from the military, was the only one possible and very successful in that it is no longer mentioned in the news at all.
Bush's reputation was not improved by this, because, objectively, he left his successor with a much more grateful starting situation than could have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama is hoping for a repeat of the miracle.
The military has again asked for more troops, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his habit of subordination, harshly criticized the stagnant White House guards.
He called for 40,000 troops to turn the tide.
The president hesitated for three months, but couldn't think of a better idea, and so he cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He pressed Europe to commit another 5,000, although he himself had originally expected at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of the Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete the process in three years, and the whole Obama doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halving of the stockpile will have the same effect as the action in Iraq.
Even in spite of the fratricidal war of the last few years, Iraqi society is relatively well structured, its leaders respect the values.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the contraindication that no one can be trusted and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they are formally correctly established, remain only facades behind which the patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balancing of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the ambiguity of the relationships that further complicates the Pakistan and Iranian influences.
The construction of a 'state capable of acting' which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation is also very unrealistic.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is alienated by his voluntarism
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and now it is on the verge of exploding.
To believe that the little soldiers who have broken out into the war cry of "early homecoming" are here to work a miracle, can only be a truly romantic soul, unimpressed by facts.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is running out.
The European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their electorate how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor which could radically affect the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and if the increased sanctions do not have an effect on the Iranians, the United States will face a very serious question of whether the problem can be solved by the use of troops.
This question must be answered in the period in which America is moving after Obama to the victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any solution will also mean a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years until the presidential election, and so there is still enough time for him to resort to another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
