Czech discovery: a substance that also acts on 'steeled' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that are designed to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that are already drug resistant.
This outweighs the disadvantage that the compound is not as potent against common virus variants as one of the existing drugs.
The AIDS disease is not curable yet.
But for patients, the combination of drugs can prolong life and prevent the multiplication of HIV viruses in the body.
But taking them is accompanied by a whole host of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of viral replication also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses against which no drugs are effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (High School of Chemical Technology) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
The metallocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the virus from replicating in a way that all the drugs we use today can't, so they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, the scientists have developed new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metal carbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multilayered cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a single metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Homemade and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV protease-induced virus cleavage, no mature infectious virus particles would be produced.
"If we stop the HIV protease, we also stop the virus from multiplying in the patient's body", explain the scientists in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the CR Academy of Sciences.
In the paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of the cage (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
