Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted to ban the construction of minarets and there is widespread concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe, an American academic, John Bowen, has written a well-founded and well-thought-out report on whether Muslims can and should be integrated into one of Europe's most secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's latest work, Why the French Don't Like Headscarves (2006), an elegant and poignant study of a contentious issue that divided and occupied the country for a decade and a half and whose impact is still being felt today.
Bowen's latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what the politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the five to six million Muslims in France what Bowen calls "Islamic free spaces".
He's a good listener, he plays back debates between teachers and students about the questions that concern them most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and gay rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly secular matters, he argues, that make up daily life, in stark contrast to the political dramas that occupy the media.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a known name, possibly except for Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss-born Arab-Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They don't have all the facts on their side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists Bowen interviewed are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts  advocates of purist Sunni Islam linked to Saudi Arabia  who today have a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But a deal requires a give and take on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French policymakers (and the intellectual elite that so passionately guards the separation of church and state) are truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may be receiving harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who in turn have had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He sees a "tightening of the value-screws" rather than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
