She said they wanted to give their first one the best.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and that it is legally allowed.
But like many Chinese, they have only a modest government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misinterpret the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with her first child.
Yes, they're taking away our ability to have more than one child.
The problem is not simply one of policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of human resources, said she only wanted one child because she was an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to caring for others, and we do not really want to".
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old owner of a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with dual careers, who are seeing birth rates fall, he said, it's all about being successful, and to do that, you have to be selfish.
The 20 to 39 year olds of today grew up seeing their parents struggle during the early days of China's capitalist experiment and they certainly don't want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, takes up a lot of the parents' time.
A mother has to give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the question of space -- "You have to rebuild your home" -- and life planning -- "When your child is nine months old, you have to have a resume ready for the best preschools".
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
