We don't want to cause too many casualties.
UN group drafts plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference - which has been characterized by wild poses and mutual blame - has set a new focus on Friday with the publication of a document that sets out an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations shouldering the biggest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the control of greenhouse gases, has both identified the remaining obstacles and indicated the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time as more than 100 top politicians from around the world arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a special UN working group, is silent on the amount of money rich countries should give to poor countries to help them cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options on the key issues, including how industrialised and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global temperature rise policy makers would take into account.
The process will be highly flexible, according to John Coequyt, a senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has compiled a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, has called "the big picture".
It outlines a possible agreement whereby the industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020 compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, the countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also gave a boost to the talks on Friday by pledging to provide US$ 3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from managing floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals for the creation of a European Union.
US climate change special envoy Todd Stern has rejected language that calls for binding greenhouse gas emission reductions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, unless funded by developed nations.
This move heralded a tougher line on China by the Obama administration than the Bush administration took less than two years ago.
The US will not sign the agreement without major emerging countries standing up and taking action, Stern said, complaining that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the cuts can be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern's comments came an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the top U.S. climate negotiator was either "unreasonable" or "highly irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the United States would not provide financial assistance to China to address global warming.
The future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake, and this has led to the emergence of fault lines both within the industrial nations and between the industrial nations and the emerging countries.
The current fight is about saving individual economies as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fretting about their respective obligations, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific necessity to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to be more aggressive in holding the very high-carbon countries accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic dominance will emerge, said Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the impacts of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will, in the best case, lead to a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the offensive by small island states is "putting political pressure on the entire political process", in part because they are now united and demanding action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the open questions still needed to be settled before the government leaders arrived in order to reach an agreement.
High-level officials, like India's environment minister Jairam Ramesh and China's vice minister, got off their planes and raced through the halls of the Bella Center for closed-door meetings and press conferences to hammer out claims that will be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people coming and going in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists hosting late-night shows where they make fun of the countries that they think are betraying and selling themselves, and contract drafts being hand-to-hand rather than e-mailed -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just beginning to build: almost all the important ministers are here now and starting on Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
"We are coming to the top league", said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global policy for Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
Britain's first 225 km/h high-speed train redefines the feeling of the day
At 5:13 on Monday morning, a whistle will pierce the darkness to announce a train departure that will revolutionize Britain's transport system.
The first high-speed commuter train in the country will reach 225 km/h from Ashfort, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
To Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, will then go Dame Kelly Holmes, on board the first Javelin shuttle service from London.
He hopes that the new service will eventually link the UK to an international rail network of faster, more reliable trains and connect the large conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected province could become vibrant commuter towns, commute times would be radically reduced, and the switch from airplanes and cars to rail would reduce national carbon emissions and road congestion.
In theory, the three major parties believe in this vision.
But the many billions of British pounds required to build a new national railway network, the inevitable planning battle and fears about environmental damage could still put the brakes on Britain's high-speed railways.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to provide the government with a feasibility study, will hand over the report to Lord Adonis on 30 December, according to the Times.
This gives him a detailed map of the next planned stage of the high-speed rail network.
The new line, which will connect London with the West Midlands, will run through urban areas and areas where the environmental impact is controversial, with a range of five metres.
In open terrain, the plan will show the concept within 25 metres of the final route.
HS2 is also to create three options for a larger high-speed rail network to the north.
Lord Adonis will respond to this in the spring.
The preferred proposed option is a Y-shaped route, where a single high-speed line would lead to the West Midlands.
The route would divide at or near Birmingham and one branch would run west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another to the north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would lead to Scotland.
"It seems to be the best-performing option", said a railroad insider.
Once completed, the journey time between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first section, which would not be opened until 2025, would enable travellers to complete the London to Birmingham route in 49 minutes, compared with just over an hour today.
The designs would allow trains to run at speeds of 400 km/h, making Britain's railway network the fastest in Europe.
The first track was designed to accommodate trains of 400 metres long and a maximum capacity of 1,100 passengers.
Up to 18 trains could be running per hour on the London-Birmingham route.
This would in turn require a terminal in London to handle 20,000 travellers per hour.
Given the capital's spatial constraints, it is expected that an existing railway station would be expanded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Railway experts say only St Pancras International or Euston have this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks this plan should be continued, but the lengthy public consultation and planning means that a final decision will not be taken until after the general election.
But even if he does move the wheels, the rail network will have to be built in sections.
The trains would first have to switch from highspeed lines to existing rail lines north of Birmingham, which would still result in a journey time of over three hours between London and Scotland.
This is considered a crucial junction point to ensure a change from air to rail, a benchmark for the rail revolution.
