The singer's production company, however, wanted to make it clear that the situation was "under control" and said that a new medical report would be available within 48 hours.
However, according to RTL, the singer's partner during the last tour, Johnny Hallyday was placed in an artificial coma to avoid "pain and complications".
However, it took 48 hours for the patient's condition to be confirmed, when he opened his eyes, RTL added.
There was no confirmation or comment from the production company at the request of the AFP.
RTL also confirms that 'certain sources' indicate that 'no drainage' was installed after its first operation in Paris.
The rocker had been operated on for a herniated disc at the international clinic at Parc Monceau.
The operation, planned for several days, was performed by neurosurgeon Stéphane Delajoux, a renowned doctor who had treated many stars.
He was not available for comment to RTL on Thursday evening.
Following the surgery on Johnny Hallyday, the singer was admitted Monday to Cedars-Sinaï Hospital in Los Angeles due to a post-operative infection.
Singer Eddy Mitchell, who is very close to Johnny Hallyday, told RTL on Thursday that his friend was going through a "deep valley". However, he assured that there was "no need to worry" about the rock musician, as he was "a good fighter".
"He had called me before he was due to fly to Los Angeles, and I told him it was nonsense to get on a plane 12 hours after such an operation, that's not how it works", said Eddy Mitchell.
On Wednesday night, the singer's producer, Jean-Claude Camus, confirmed that Johnny Hallyday "is responding well to the antibiotics" and that "the infection is contained".
Mr Camus also said that he had spoken to Laeticia, the singer's wife, and that he had not felt any particular anxiety.
However, concern over the singer's health had been growing since he spent nine days in hospital in July after a crash on his yacht.
Two months later, to the general astonishment of the public, it was announced that Johnny Hallyday had undergone a "small operation for colon cancer", followed by a mild infection.
At the end of September, the singer recorded his long "Tour 66" as planned as a farewell tour.
Since then, however, every health issue has been extensively commented upon, and fans and journalists have not missed the fact that the singer had difficulty moving on stage.
It was not until mid-November that the people around him had to be hospitalized again.
Euro 2009: Bousquet takes first place in his favourite distance
Frenchman Frédérick Bousquet, a three-time medalist at the 2009 World Championships, won an international title on Thursday in his favourite distance, the 50m freestyle, at the Euro 2009 on the short course in Istanbul.
On the first day of this competition, the last time polyurethane suits were allowed, there were only three world records, while a veritable record flood was expected.
One record was bettered by Hungarian Evelyn Verraszto over 4 x 200 m relays and the other two by Russia in men's 4 x 50 m relays.
The loss was a blow to Bousquet, who was trying to take the world record in the 50m freestyle, which he holds in the large pool (20.94).
In one of the two King's Distances in swimming, the 50m freestyle, the 28-year-old Frenchman claimed the title in 20.53 seconds, in a final with ten swimmers at the start (usually there are eight) - a first at international level.
Bousquet beat the Croatian Duje Draganja (20.70) and the Russian Sergey Fesikov (20.84), but he did not manage to break the world record (20.30) as planned.
"You can always hope for something bigger and in this case I said if the world record is within my reach, I'll try".
Like Bousquet, almost all swimmers started in polyurethane suits, which are banned from 1 January 2010.
With 238 world records since February 2008, these combinations end their epic in Istanbul, which began in 1999 at the same competition.
The combination didn't pay off for German Paul Biedermann, two-time world champion in Rome this summer and world record holder.
The young swimmer failed to improve on his best time over 400m freestyle (3:32.77), but he still won with the second best time in his career (3:34.55), ahead of Russian Nikita Lobintsev (3:35.75) and Danish Mads Glaesner (3:36.82).
"I didn't give it my all this time.
I knew I couldn't set a world record today, but I defended my title and did my job".
"Lobintsev will be a serious opponent in the future", explained Biedermann.
USA: Zola's tombstone is estimated at $1.5 million
A Roman tombstone discovered in the possession of French writer Emile Zola was valued at $1.5 million over its original value on Thursday, according to art dealer Sotheby's.
This slab is six feet long and two feet high, and it dates from the third century C.E. It has always been valued at $150,000 to $250,000.
The marble, which "represents four scenes of Dionysus in sophisticated architectural decoration surrounded by satyr and Bacchus figures, is a rare piece, there are only four or five of them in the world", Florent Heintz, vice president of Roman and Egyptian antiquities at Sotheby's, told AFP on Tuesday.
It was sold in less than a hundred pieces.
"The sale is still on, but this is certainly the piece that buyers have bid the most for so far", Sotheby's spokesman Dan Abernethy told AFP.
The discovery of this marble piece by Emile Zola goes back a long way.
The plate was kept in Rome for almost 300 years in the famous Borghese family collection, then it appeared piece by piece in the bathroom of the French actress Cécile Sorel, who used it in her Paris hotel, and in the bathroom of Paul Reynaud, minister in the Third French Republic and president of the Council before Marshal Pétain came to power.
The next 50 years are in the dark.
While searching the Louvre's database, Florent Heintz discovered that this plate was part of an "Emile Zola legacy" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the fresco "Rougon-Macquart".
Zelaya's attempt to leave Honduras for Mexico has been foiled
On Thursday, Mexico declared the conditions for the transfer of the deposed Honduran president Manuel Zelaya to domestic soil no longer acceptable, after the latter rejected the coup government's escort as unacceptable.
After a late-night phone call with President Zelaya, there seems to be a disagreement about how to carry out the transfer, said Mexico's Foreign Minister Patricia Espinosa.
According to the immigration department, the plane, which was chartered by the Mexican government and arrived in Salvador on Wednesday to transfer Mr. Zelayas, returned to its place of departure.
The coup government wanted to force Mr Zelaya to "resign" and to seek political asylum for him abroad under escort.
The deposed president, however, refused to do so, wishing to return to Mexico as the most welcome incumbent head of state.
The coup regime "has failed again by trying to get me to resign at my expense (...), they wanted me to resign", Zelaya told Radio Globo on Thursday, in which he has been a frequent speaker since the beginning of the political crisis that has lasted five months in the Central American country.
I can stay here for ten years, here is my guitar, added the deposed president, who had fled to the Brazilian embassy in Tegucigalpa two and a half months ago, with a few strokes of the chord.
The Mexican embassy has asked us to accompany it, but unfortunately we cannot accept it because it does not include a request for asylum, Oscar Raul Matute, the interior minister of the coup government, told Honduran radio HRN on Wednesday.
The EU is also calling for the release of the hostages, and for the release of the hostages.
The President of the Republic of Honduras, Mr Gonzalez, had said that he would only leave Honduras if he was the President of the Honduran people.
The rumors of Mr Zelaya's departure had on Wednesday mobilized the supporters of the deposed president, who had gathered around the Brazilian embassy, whereupon the military there had stepped up its efforts.
Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim criticized the position of the coup government.
This, he said, revealed the marginal character of this government in the face of international standards.
Zelaya, who had been close to the socialist Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez, was overthrown on June 28, the day of the referendum he organized to prepare his re-election, against the advice of the Supreme Court, the army and the Congress.
He had returned from exile in Costa Rica on September 21 and had sought refuge in the Brazilian embassy.
If he leaves, he will be arrested for high treason, which he is accused of by the judiciary, according to the coup government.
The coupled President Roberto Micheletti has succeeded in organising a presidential election on 29 November to replace M. Zelaya.
The United States has recognized Porfirio Lobo in the course of the disputed election, but Latin American countries such as Venezuela, Argentina and Brazil have rejected him.
Three days later, the Congress voted overwhelmingly against Mr Zelaya's return to office until the end of his term on 27 January.
Wall Street on the rise, US trade balance fuels optimism
The New York Stock Exchange closed on Thursday with a high, the figures of the American trade balance show a recovery in the prices of the United States and their partners: the Dow Jones rose by 0.67%, the Nasdaq by 0.33%.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose from 68.78 to 10,405.83 points, according to the stock market closing figures, while the Nasdaq, dominated by technology, rose from 7.13 to 2,190.06 points.
The Standard & Poor's 500 extended index was written down by 0.58 % (6.40 points) to 1,102.35 points.
There is good news from various sectors, said Lindsey Piegza of FTN Financial.
This is an anecdote, however, given that the market is only focused on 'half-full glasses', she said.
According to Peter Cardillo of Avalon Partners, investors are primarily focused on the US trade balance figures, "which show an improvement in activity in the fourth quarter".
The United States trade deficit fell by 7.6% to $32.9 billion in October compared with September.
The analysts, on the contrary, had expected a deficit increase.
Both imports and exports have increased.
The big news is the increase in the total volume of trade, especially in goods exports, reflecting the economic growth of the United States' main trading partners, commented Christopher Cornell of the business research site Economy.com.
In contrast, unemployment claims in the United States have risen against expectations in the past week, reaching 474,000.
However, the average number of new job seekers during the past four weeks "has fallen to its lowest point of the year", said Scott Marcouiller of Wells Fargo Advisors.
The bond market has gone down.
