Cuba: Hundreds of ruling partisans blow the whistle of "Ladies in White"
On Thursday, several hundred partisans in power in Cuba attacked the wives of political prisoners who had gathered in Havana for the World Day of Human Rights and also disrupted another rally, which resulted in the temporary arrest of a dozen or so dissidents.
Around forty "Ladies in White", wives or close relatives of political prisoners, were booed in the open by partisans of the government of Raul Castro, just as they were marching into the center of the capital to demand the release of the political prisoners, an AFP journalist confirmed.
Down with the Yankees! "Mercenaries!" "The street belongs to the revolutionaries!" "Long live Fidel and Raul!" the empowered partisans chanted with raised fists towards the dissidents.
The latter were escorted by civilian agents who had appeared to "ensure their protection".
A similar demonstration against the Ladies in White was held in Havana the previous evening, but no one was injured or arrested.
In the Vedado district, a dozen dissidents who were also attending Thursday's International Human Rights Day demonstration were temporarily detained by civilian police, an AFP reporter confirmed.
The police forcefully forced dissidents who had been detained by government partisans to board civilian vehicles, according to the journalist.
Temporary detention of dissidents in such circumstances is usually limited to a few hours.
As candidates for the European Parliament's 2005 Sakharov Prize, the Ladies in White organized an unauthorized march to "Ask for the release of all political prisoners" which, according to the dissident list, includes some 200 people, said Laura Pollan, one of the leaders whose husband Hector Maceda is serving a 20-year prison sentence.
Mr Maceda is one of the 75 Cuban dissidents jailed in March 2003, 53 of whom are still behind bars.
The Cuban authorities see the opponents of the regime as "mercenaries" or "agents" in the service of the declared arch-enemy, the United States.
A rarity in itself is that the Cuban television reported on the demonstration events that took place on Thursday between militant pro-government fighters and "counter-revolutionaries".
Cuba, which is led by a single party, the Communist Party, is regularly accused by European or American NGOs of violating rights and freedoms, in particular freedom of expression.
A maniac kills an 80-year-old with a knife and leaves five wounded in Clichy-la-Garenne .
A maniac armed with two knives killed an eighty-year-old man and injured five others in the city of Clichy-la-Garenne (Hauts-de-Seine) late Friday afternoon during the main business hours.
According to initial reports, the 28-year-old attacker had wounded the 80-year-old for an as yet unknown reason in or outside a pharmacy on Boulevard Jean-Jaures with two knives and this, according to police, in the presence of witnesses.
The old man, born in 1929, according to a representative of the Alliance police syndicate, died in hospital as a result of his injuries.
In or outside the same pharmacy, he's got a couple with a pregnant woman.
The man, about thirty, intervened and was injured.
The first two victims were taken to hospital with serious injuries, where the 80-year-old died.
The other man is in critical condition, with vital organs apparently affected, according to police sources.
The pregnant woman has been sick as a result of the events and has been hospitalized in a "state of shock", according to a police source.
The armed man, who according to police appeared to be under the influence of alcohol or drugs, is said to have immediately escaped onto the street, the flat Boulevard Jean Jaures.
He injured two other passers-by, apparently by accident: a man in his thirties and a man in his forties, the latter of the two seriously.
The scenario was kept in the dark in the evening.
He was armed with two butcher knives, which he carried crossed behind his back, said Arnaud Pressé, a member of the Alliance syndicate in the Hauts-de-Seine region.
According to witnesses gathered by the AFP, several passers-by, including teenagers, tried to restrain the madman.
I saw a guy in a three-piece with a green vest.
Three youths tried to enter.
They didn't make it because the guy was well-built, reported Alberto, a waiter at a nearby bar.
A horde attacked him, he added, including a city policeman who broke his wrist.
Still on Boulevard Jean-Jaures, at the level of house number 61, two municipal police officers, including their superior, tried to arrest the armed man and were wounded with knife blades, according to police information.
The incident took place in one of the main arteries of Clichy-la-Garenne, where a number of shops are located.
Passersby approached me to tell me that there's an injured person outside.
I went outside and saw a 70-year-old person lying on the floor, I put him in the first aid position and noticed a gaping wound in the stomach area, said Frédéric Allione, a 35-year-old pharmacist, to AFP.
Five minutes later, a second person, about thirty years old, came in with cuts.
State police forces finally arrested the man who was not carrying any identification papers.
The prosecutor's office of Nanterre has instructed the district office of the criminal police of Hauts-de-Seine (SDPJ 92) to investigate the case.
The lunatic was admitted to hospital on Thursday night.
Given his condition, he has not yet been tried in court.
A police source doesn't rule out a mental hospital.
According to another police source, six officers were called to restrain him at the police station in Clichy, where he had been taken.
He was "in a state of over-excitement" like "all the mentally confused of this kind, in whom the forces are released during the passage of the Tathers".
USA: Polanski's lawyer again calls for the prosecution to be stopped
The lawyer for French-Polish filmmaker Roman Polanski has repeatedly called on Thursday in Los Angeles (California, western United States) to drop the prosecution against his client, who is currently on trial in his home in Switzerland for a moral offence committed more than 30 years ago.
Chad Hummel, lawyer for the director of The Pianist, has testified before three judges of the Second District of California Court of Appeal about gross miscarriages of justice during the trial in 1977.
I am asking for a reprieve immediately,' Mr Hummel said, before adding that the behaviour of Judge Laurence Rittenband, who was handling the case at the time, 'was a bit of a shock'.
According to him, before the judge, the late Judge Rittenband, delivered his verdict, he had a discussion with a prosecutor who told him that Roman Polanski deserved to be imprisoned - which was a serious procedural error.
This discussion was raised in the documentary "Roman Polanski: wanted and desired", by the prominent prosecutor David Wells.
Mr Wells had finally declared at the end of September that the authors of the documentary had "lied".
If the Court refuses to dismiss the criminal proceedings, Mr Hummel requests that a trial be held which would enable him to present the evidence in support of his argument.
The prosecution, for its part, has repeated the line of evidence already explained at first instance, i.e. that a discussion to set aside the facts against the accused cannot be seriously considered as long as Roman Polanski does not appear in court.
The 76-year-old director had fled the United States in 1978, before the conviction for "illegal sexual relations" with a minor of 13 years.
He hasn't been back to the States since.
Los Angeles County Deputy District Attorney Phyllis Asayama had stated that Roman Polanski "must be there to witness the trial".
"Do you want to spread the message in this case, not just to (Roman Polanski) but to other defendants, that escape is a way out?" asks Ms Asayma.
In their view, "the filmmaker is asking the court for a favor and thus disregards its authority".
One of the three judges  who now have 90 days to announce their decision  even emphasised "that there are other alternatives to escape".
Hummel was not the only one who had asked for the prosecution of Roman Polanski to be suspended.
The lawyer of Samantha Geimer, the victim, also demanded the suspension of the criminal proceedings.
She reminded her client that she could no longer tolerate being harassed by any re-emergence of the Polanski affair, adding: "No one in this room can say that this process was fair.
Thirty-two years is enough".
Roman Polanski was arrested in Switzerland on September 26th, on an American arrest warrant.
After spending two months behind bars, he was sentenced to house arrest in his chalet in Gstaad, in anticipation of possible extradition.
