Miss World again in South Africa
After a month-long tour of South Africa, the 112 Miss World contestants will cross the final hurdle on Saturday to realize their dream of being voted the most beautiful woman in the world in front of a billion television viewers.
Five of them have already secured their place in the semi-finals of this major beauty fair, which is being held in the Johannesburg area for the second time in a row.
Miss Japan Eruza Sasaki, Perla Beltran Acosta from Mexico, Mariatu Kargbo from Sierra Leone, Kaiane Aldorino from Gilbratar and Yanbing Ma from Canada were crowned Miss Sportive or Miss Topmodel during their stay in Africa.
This was a veritable whirlwind of pleasure.
Touring beautiful cities, such as Port Elizabeth, Durban and Cape Horn, was simply extraordinary.
I have seen many things and had many experiences! said Miss Sierra Leone enthusiastically.
This competition will be the ninth to be held in South Africa and will be broadcast live from Midrand, north of Johannesburg, on Saturday, starting at 5pm (15pm CET).
I can't think of a more beautiful place to give my crown.
It was a fascinating experience.
I'm happy to have had this experience twice, underlined Miss World Ksenia Sukhinova in the heat of the South African summer.
For the young Russian, her second stay in South Africa was marked by numerous exchanges of experience with the candidates and the rediscovery of "stunning landscapes".
After a month of gala, auditions, press conferences and safari, the Miss is now focusing on the competition.
Pooja Chopra, from India, hopes to follow in the footsteps of Priyanka Chopra, who was elected in 2000 and will be present at this election, and Aishwarya Rai, who was elected in 1994 and both became Bollywood stars.
Of course, it is every woman's dream to be crowned the most beautiful woman in the world, but it's not just about looks.
We are ambassadors of our country and I want to come home with the crown, Miss India throws in a wide smile.
According to the organizers, this 59th edition will be highlighted with music and dance.
The candidates will be in traditional costumes and, not to be forgotten, in swimming trunks.
The show will be hosted by Chinese television host Angela Chow, South African former beauty queen Michelle McLean and Miss World committee chair Steve Douglas.
South Africa has shown that it knows how to welcome the world with a warmth and pride that are second to none, assures Miss World's chairwoman Julia Morley.
The candidates have, as last year, taken a safari touring the famous township in Soweto, but this time they have tried the bicycle and the local cuisine.
The most extraordinary thing, however, was the meeting with the South African President, Mr Jacob Zuma, who shook hands with them.
Not unusual for a head of state, Miss Sierra Leone remarked.
But her fondest memory is undoubtedly the draw in Cape Town (southwest) for the World Cup in June 2010, a way for the country to promote the event.
I'm mixed up with people I'd probably never get close to otherwise.
I will certainly return for the 2010 World Cup, enthusiastically promised Miss Italy, Alice Taticchi.
The news about Johnny Hallyday is "very positive", according to his son David.
The news about Johnny Hallyday is "very positive", his son David assured on Friday upon his arrival at Los Angeles airport to visit his father, who has been in hospital there for several days.
The news is very positive.
He is very strong, everything is going very well, David Hallyday told the press as he stepped off the plane, which arrived from Paris shortly after 1 p.m. local time (21 a.m. CET).
The son of the singer, who appeared relaxed, assured that he would go "as quickly as possible" to the hospital Cedars-Sinaï, where Johnny Hallyday was admitted on Monday for a bacterial infection after surgery for a herniated disc on November 26 in Paris.
The singer was "put into an artificial coma in Los Angeles this night to relieve his severe pain and to be able to carry out his treatment, the press service announced.
Johnny Hallyday was placed in an induced coma by doctors at Cedars-Sinai Hospital in Los Angeles, where he was admitted Monday due to a bacterial infection following a herniated disc surgery on November 26 in Paris.
The singer had to undergo another operation in the night from Wednesday to Thursday because of the morbid changes caused by the last operation.
His wife Laeticia attended a school event at the French high school in Los Angeles on Friday morning, where their daughter Jade is attending school, an AFP photographer noted.
The head of orthopedic and traumatology surgery at the Hôpital Pitié-Salpêtrière, Yves Catoné, announced that he would visit the singer on Monday at the hospital in Los Angeles.
The producer has put a heavy burden on the neurosurgeon Dr. Stephane Delajoux, who operated on the singer on November 26th at the Clinique Internationale du Parc Monceau in Paris.
We were told that he had committed the most heinous massacre.
The surgeons from Los Angeles said they were "totally outraged", Mr. Camus explained.
I have heard that a possible legal action will be taken, he said.
Jean-Claude Camus believes that Johnny Hallyday "traveled to Los Angeles much too quickly and with the permission of the Paris surgeon".
I personally spoke to the doctor on the phone, who assured me that he considered this trip to be completely unproblematic, which was very surprising to me, since I had already had two operations on my herniated disc, he added.
Shortly before, he announced on RTL that the singer had apparently left the hospital after the operation "without drainage, without everything".
Dr. Stéphane Delajoux is well known in the artistic circles.
He had operated on the actress Marie Trintignant in Vilnius a few days before her death, at a clinic in Neuilly-sur-Seine where he was practicing at the time.
In 2007, he also operated on actress Charlotte Gainsbourg to resorbe a hematoma after a brain hemorrhage.
But he is also a doctor with a dubious reputation, having been convicted several times for botched surgeries and, not to mention, for tax evasion and fraud.
Mr Olivier Metzner, lawyer for the medical association, described him as "a man without scruples" who had to answer "regularly" to the board of directors and who "was anything but commendable".
After a few days of silence, Dr. Stéphane Delajoux made a statement on Friday through his lawyer, Mr. David Koubbi.
He stated that the surgery had "gone perfectly" and that the post-operative examinations had been "normal".
The operation "did not produce any bleeding and therefore did not require any drainage", he added.
In any case, the tour of the singer, whose health problems have been increasing since last summer, seems to be in question.
It is quite clear that the tour is a little short for a continuation on 8 January (in Amiens), Mr Camus explained.
The UDF (Union for French Democracy) is strongly calling on the Nouveau Centre party to stop using its seal
The alliance of parties overseen by François Bayrou's MoDem party on Friday reacted strongly to an attempt by the Nouveau Centre party chairman Hervé Morin to take over the seal of the party once founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing, and urged him, under threat of legal action, not to use this seal on any document.
Hervé Morin publicly announces his intention to take over this UDF seal, as he believes that François Bayrou would not be worthy to defend this political heritage after having reached out to the left.
The Minister of Defence, whose party is the UMP, wanted to reaffirm this strategy on Saturday before the National Council of the NC.
In support of his efforts, he had received the support of the Member of Parliament Hervé de Charette (formerly UMP, now NC), who claims ownership of the UDF mark, having been the first to apply for that mark in 2004 at the 'Institut national de la propriété industrielle'.
However, the office of the UDF, the alliance of parties overseen by the friends of François Bayrous, broke the silence and made it clear that they would not allow themselves to be expropriated and set the Minister and the Member of Parliament a deadline, under threat of legal action, to no longer use this seal and to transfer the ownership rights of the trademark to them.
You have made numerous statements in recent days that you would propose to your political movement to adopt the UDF seal ++, the alliance of parties wrote in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the bureau, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez, of the MoDem party, and Senator Jean Arthuis of the centrist alliance.
You also thought that you had the right to have the name of this movement, the slogan of the current UDF, printed on your political material and on the home page of your website.
As you know, you have no right to use this seal, the office of the UDF explained and called on the party NC to "immediately remove the mention of the name of the UDF from all material and from (its) website".
In addition, Hervé de Charette was required to 'transfer the ownership of the mark to its legal successors'.
If you refuse, we will take legal action against you to ensure respect for the law and to defend the legitimate rights of UDF members, the signatories warned.
In their letter, they stress that the UDF has been a full-fledged political movement since 1978 and recall that Morin and his friends "made the choice" to leave it in 2007 to form a rival movement, as others had already done in 2002 to form the UMP party.
The Nouveau Centre party therefore has no right to use the UDF (Union for French Democracy) seal.
They also recall that the last UDF congress in 2007 approved the three-year membership of the MoDem party and the creation of a bureau to defend 'the material and moral interests' of the movement founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the Office continues, 'he had not been a member of the UDF for three years when he applied for the trade name' but had become a member of the UMP.
He profits in a scandalous and fraudulent manner from the lack of the deposit of the acronym UDF to do this for himself.
They also point out that this recklessness is on the way to becoming a crime, and they ironically point out the NC's strategy: "It seems more dignified to us, in politics as in life, to make a name for oneself rather than to try to escape anonymity by fraudulently acquiring a name to which one has no legal claim".
The Affaire Liliane Bettencourt: François-Marie Banier is convicted of exploiting the weak
The Court of Justice of Nanterre decided on Friday to try the artist François-Marie Banier to determine whether, as the daughter of the billionaire Liliane Bettencourt claims, he took advantage of a weak moment of the eighty-year-old to steal part of her fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his star photos, will appear in court on April 15 and 16, 2010 for exploiting weakness, a crime punishable by a maximum three-year prison sentence and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will indeed be a trial in this affair worthy of the saga of one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter are fighting and at the same time holding the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetics empire.
The 15th Criminal Chamber has also ordered a medical examination of Liliane Bettencourt, 87, which will be carried out jointly by three doctors.
The heiress and main shareholder of L'Oréal has so far refused to submit to such an investigation, especially under the conditions laid down by the Nanterre public prosecutor's office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday are to submit a report before 10 March 2010 clearly stating whether and at what times Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness.
I think she's going to submit to these tests.
I will speak to her, said Mrs Bettencourt's lawyer, Mr Georges Kiejman, after the hearing.
