The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: six feet long and five feet wide, it walked on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body features, reported Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's issue of the journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the relationship, the distribution and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
"We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for Triassic fossils", says team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by the researchers as new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of five individuals.
Finding confirms theories about early dinosaur history
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, mostly found in single fragments".
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share this enthusiasm.
The find is not particularly spectacular, but it does confirm some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current view, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these Ur-dinosaurs is mostly controversial.
For example, experts debate when lizards split into their three main lines of evolution: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor, and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "long-tailed" and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithischians, which included the triceratops and stegosauruses.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced features, says Nesbitt.
For example, the skull of Tawa hallae, the researchers found evidence of air sacs, as the descendants of the theropods, the birds, have.
Thanks to the air sacs, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In the case of the Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light-weight bones, it is likely that the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
According to this theory, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America to all continents, which then formed a single landmass as the supercontinent Pangaea.
This is explained by the fact that the team, along with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, argue the researchers.
"We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America", says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says paleontologist Martin Sander of Bonn.
He feels that the picture may be distorted because South America has a very large number of primitive dinosaur fossils, while other continents have very little.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare side-line of the reptilian lineage to the dominant land vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Triassic period, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, including the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flying dinosaurs, and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the Triassic-Jurassic boundary became extinct.
Success stories did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction, where the dinosaurs just happened to survive, but the other reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped to give birth to a group of animals that had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had given birth to a shadow life: the mammals.
