The worlds of dreams
Some people in their waking state see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It's not just in the case of the mentally ill and the drug addicts that the lines between imagination and reality blur.
As long as it's in your sleep, it's fine.
When we lie with our eyes closed in our dark rooms, we are free to indulge in the wildest imaginations and fantasies.
But in the modern Western world, those who experience a dreamlike state while awake, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or addicted to drugs, or at least strange.
But such images and voices are not limited to the mentally ill or to drug addicts.
It's our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes blur the lines between dreams, delusions, and reality.
Traumatic altered states of consciousness can occur in a variety of forms, at best we call them visions, at worst we call them delusions.
Although the causes and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard of Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the shamanic states of rapture, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of the brain's neurotransmitters - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and acetylcholine - is disturbed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very common during schizophrenic psychosis.
