The illusions are a cruel reality
About 1 percent of the population will develop schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric hospitals, it is the second most common disorder after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, the affected person is usually unable to distinguish between the internal and external world, and they fall into an over-excited state that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, delusions of relationship or persecution.
Especially common is the hearing of voices - voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The person is unable to distinguish between what is important and what is unimportant, the brain is unable to filter out disturbing signals, and the mind is flooded with impressions.
Like dreams, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate in deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at the University Hospital Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he is in a passive role, he is, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
They are often unable to reconcile reality, and the delusions are a cruel reality, beyond awakening.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in dreams, says Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality perceived in psychosis is fundamentally preserved".
The delusions and hallucinations are rooted in reality, the alienation of experience takes place in the real frame.
Why our brain is so capricious is still a mystery to researchers.
"Extraordinary circumstances can cause any person to lose touch with reality for a short time", says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers believe that those affected have minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the brain's neural maturation is disrupted early in development, for example by a viral illness of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disruption of the neuronal system comes about, and how it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis if the disposition is present.
