The borderline between dream and hallucination
In our world, which is too focused on consciousness, imaginary experience is unfortunately often pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the clinic for psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a painful, painful disease, but it also has positive, creative aspects -- delusion is also a work of art out of desperation.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of traumatically altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer believes to be real and which, even in retrospect, cannot be distinguished from the waking state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness occurs in extreme trauma or disease-related situations, for example in polyradiculite patients who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
When a person is threatened with loss of self and world, for example by permanent, complete immobility, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with a separate, imaginary world that is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
It's a borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is made present in the imagination.
An intensive form of meaning-making and meaning-giving in a situation that is intolerable in itself, which allows us humans to have our own creative capacity, not to be submerged in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even in the memory later
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart-change" as a soul-saving action.
At the age of 49, after heart valve surgery and subsequent heart transplant, his consciousness travels for days while his body is condemned to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make drugs from blood.
Taken by a Greek man on a motorcycle to his homeland, he surfs his hospital bed in the alpine snow and meets a Korean mafioso.
He is completely absorbed in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream for Claussen.
Dreams are a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories of my mental journeys are still vivid to me after years and in minor details.
More vivid and intense than anything I've ever experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows the horizon of our other life experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneroids, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug addiction demonstrate how fragile our inner images of external reality are even in the waking state.
Any alteration in the state of consciousness, sums up psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality".
An experience that can be very enriching.
