75% of working mothers have experienced problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and Careers of Women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of women in employment see their career opportunities on the labour market as being restricted by their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are wide differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children depending on whether women work or not and if so, what type of occupation they have.
Those of them who do not work outside the home, who work part-time or who do not have a fixed contract of employment are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women in permanent employment, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"The average duration of first childbirth for women in the 35-49 age group with a fixed job is 3.7 years after moving in together, rising to 4.1 years for women with a fixed job, who took longer to do so and who moved in together and had their first child much later.
In addition, the nature of work also has a major impact on motherhood, although less so than the calendar in terms of readiness for conception", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor to be taken into account in the age of women at marriage and at the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference was also observed in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between 35 and 49 years old, depending on whether they had only a high school diploma or a higher education, became mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 or 32.1 respectively.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While women with a high school diploma marry before their first permanent job and have their first child, women with a medium or high school diploma do the opposite, seeking a permanent job and marrying before they have their first child, Delgado notes.
