Assisting with braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the antilock braking system (ABS) in the past and as with the ESP stability control system now, emergency braking systems must become compulsory in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered cars and light vans, with a grace period until the end of February 2011 for the remaining vehicles.
The measure adopted by the European Union is designed to improve the protection of pedestrians, but the way these braking systems work also helps to prevent many road accidents.
The role of the emergency brake assistant is to apply more pressure to the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects by the brake force applied by the driver to the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exert this pressure to the end.
According to a study commissioned by the manufacturer of components for Bosch vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not even reached the brake pedal before the collision, and half had not brake at full speed.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake assist system, on the other hand, works its way into the braking system with maximum force, thus reducing the braking time and thus the braking distance a car travels when braking.
According to an EU study, up to 1100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is estimated that one in four accidents with personal injury could be prevented - once so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (by radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time applying a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant applies maximum pressure to the brakes to minimize damage.
