In these days of storms and accidents, not only the car repair shops earn
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are hauled to the workshops where an appraiser must assess the damage and the cost of repairs.
No two accidents are alike and calculating the cost of parts and man hours can be a long and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs, which are between EUR 20 000 and EUR 30 000 per person, including parts and hours of work, can take up to two or three hours.
In contrast, with the help of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes
This is why almost 100% of the appraisers use this type of system.
Accident and repair assessment and application service providers collect the information they receive from manufacturers, process it and provide it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American Solera group, is the market leader; 80% of all assessments are produced with its products.
The other two companies competing in the market for assessment and reporting tools are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data supplied by the manufacturers is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of them providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the whole of the previous fifteen years.
As soon as a new car is on the market, work begins for the companies.
It is a difficult task, because every one of the thousand vehicle parts has to be catalogued and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which different parts of the vehicle can be "clicked".
If the model is a big seller, the work can be completed in a week if the process proceeds quickly.
The Commission has also been asked to draw up a list of the most important products which are likely to be sold in the future, and to draw up a list of the most important products which are likely to be sold in the future.
Among the more exclusive models, they have information on the Porsche models, for example, but not on the Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the number of vehicles on the road, it is over 99%.
Audatex has eight centres worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) for the purpose of carrying out the documentation and compiling the databases, each of which is specialised in certain brands.
The national headquarters are in Alcobendas (Madrid).
More than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euro annually in the development of these databases.
They're taking in 2.5 million pieces of data every month, and their customers are getting updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is for repairs and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the fair or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this service in Spain, but does in the United States.
By reviewing the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an overview of the kind of support it provides to the industry experts.
